  "referred_to_by": [
    {
      "type": "LinguisticObject",
      "content": "The **Van Marum Large Electrostatic Generator** — the **largest flat-plate frictional electrostatic machine ever built**, and one of the most important surviving scientific instruments of the 18th century. It remains the centerpiece of the Teylers Museum instrument room. Two coaxial glass discs (1.65 m diameter each) rotate against friction cushions, generating static charge collected by brass combs and stored in a battery of approximately 100 Leyden jars across four complete sets — the largest Leyden jar battery ever assembled. Capable of generating approximately 330,000 V (sparks to 60 cm); combined with the full battery, voltages approaching 720 kV. **Van Marum first observed the smell of ozone using this machine in 1785**, though he did not identify the gas as such.\n\nCommissioned by **Martinus van Marum** (1750–1837), first director of Teylers Museum, from instrument maker **John Cuthbertson** in May 1783. Cuthbertson was paid 3,250 guilders. The wooden support and cabinetwork were designed by architect **Leendert Viervant the Younger** (1752–**1801**). The machine was placed in the newly opened Oval Room on **Christmas Day (eerste kerstdag), 25 December 1784**. The inscription on the machine reads: *J. CUTHBERTSON Fecit Amsterdam MDCCLXXXIV*.",
